Of course, this is a convex quadratics in the variables $a,$ $b,$ and $c, so the minimum occurs when the gradient vanishes.  Setting the partial derivatives with respect to $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ to zero, we have $4a = 3b = 12c.$Springing from the constraint that $a + b + c = 1,$ we find $b = 3/7,$ $a = 12/21,$ and $c = 7/21.  Since the second partial derivative matrix is an identity matrix, the Hessian is positive definite, and so we have a global minimum at the point $(a,b,c) = (12/21, 3/7, 7/21)$ <answer> $0.72$

Yes, cake numbers are the maximum number of regions that can be created inside a cake to be served slicing it $n-1$ times. Such regions can be looked up in OEIS. The cake numbers for non-negative integers $n$ are $C_n = 1, 2, 4, 8, 15, 26, 42, 64, 93, 130, 176, 232, 301, \ldots$ The cake numbers also extend for negative integers. For this extension, first inductively define
\begin{align*}
   &= \begin{bmatrix}
         1 &  -1 \\
         -1 &  1
        \end{bmatrix},
         \\ &\begin{bmatrix}
   \tbinom{2}{2} &   \tbinom{2}{3}    \\
   \tbinom{1}{2} & -\tbinom{0}{2}
 \end{bmatrix},
         \\ &\begin{bmatrix}
     \tbinom{3}{2} & \tbinom{3}{3} & \tbinom{3}{4} \\
     \tbinom{2}{2} & -\tbinom{1}{2} & \tbinom{0}{2}\\
     \tbinom{1}{2} & -\tbinom{0}{2} & \tbinom{-1}{2}
   \end{bmatrix},
   \\ &\begin{bmatrix}
     \tbinom{4}{2} & \tbinom{4}{3}  & \tbinom{4}{4}&\tbinom{4}{5} \\
     \tbinom{3}{2} & -\tbinom{2}{2} & \tbinom{1}{2} & \tbinom{0}{2}\\
     \tbinom{2}{2} & \tbinom{1}{2} & -\tbinom{0}{2} & \tbinom{-1}{2}\\
     \tbinom{1}{2} & \tbinom{0}{2} & \tbinom{-1}{2} & \tbinom{-2}{2}
   \end{bmatrix}, \ \mbox{etc.}
   \end{align*}

